  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT263-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">ippāṭṭaṉṉai veṟi (C2: aṉṉai veṟiyāṭṭu) eṭukkak karutā niṉṟāḷ “iṉi yām
          itaṟku eṉ kolō ceyaṟ pālatu” eṉat tōḻi talaimakaṭkut talaimakaṉ ciṟaippuṟamākak kūṟiyatu. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Spoken, while HE is behind the hedge, to HER, by the
          confidante, saying “Mother is [still] irresolute [whether] to take up the Veṟi dance; now
          what is the part to be done by us about this?” </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT263">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> maṟikkura laṟuttut tiṉaippirap pirīic</l>
          <l> cellāṟṟuk kavalaip palliyaṅ kaṟaṅkat</l>
          <l> tōṟṟa mallatu nōykkumarun tākā</l>
          <l> vēṟṟupperun teyvam palavuṭaṉ vāḻttip</l>
          <l> pēeyk koḷīiya ḷivaḷeṉap paṭuta</l>
          <l> ṉōtak kaṉṟē tōḻi mālvarai</l>
          <l> maḻaiviḷai yāṭu nāṭaṉaip</l>
          <l> piḻaiyē mākiya nāmitaṟ paṭavē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>[In response to this] pain is fitting <note place="foot">I.e. to this, pain is the
            proper reaction on her part? Or as a punishment for someone else, namely, HIM, who has
            let this happen instead of marrying her in time?</note> , friend,</l>
          <l rend="indent">upon the event <note place="foot">In my view the construction is as
            follows: the v. n. <term xml:lang="ta">paṭutal</term> (in appositional relation to the
            inf. <term xml:lang="ta">paṭa</term> at the end) as indirect object to <term
                xml:lang="ta">takkaṉṟu</term> , on which depend three absolutives ( <term
                xml:lang="ta">uṟuttu, iṟīi</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">vāḻtti</term> ), while the
            third abs. <term xml:lang="ta">vāḻtti</term> governs the negative abs. <term
                xml:lang="ta">ākā</term> , to which, in turn, the inf. <term xml:lang="ta">kaṟaṅka</term>
            is subordinate.</note> of [their] saying: “she is possessed by a spirit!”,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">cutting a kid's throat [and] preparing millet offerings</l>
          <l rend="indent2">[and] praising with many [songs] different great gods,</l>
          <l rend="indent">without [that] being a remedy for the pain apart from appearance, <note
              place="foot">Does <term xml:lang="ta">tōṟṟam</term> denote here something that looks
            as it actually is not, that is, translated freely, a good spectacle? T.V.G. explains it
            as the appearance of the god who takes possession of the entranced priest.</note>
          </l>
          <l rend="indent2">while many instruments are sounding on the crossing</l>
          <l rend="indent8">of moving rivers.</l>
          <l>That this [should] happen to us who haven't wronged <note place="foot">What is the
            impact of <term xml:lang="ta">piḻaiyēm</term> here? There is no point in saying that SHE
            has stood by HIM, because it is her relatives who have started the exorcism rite. The
            question might be whether she has done something wrong with the man from the land. But <term
                xml:lang="ta">nāṭaṉai</term> is a marked accusative, and consequently a direct
            object.</note>
          </l>
          <l rend="indent2">the man from a land, where rain is playing <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">maḻai viḷaiyāṭu</term> : or "where clouds are playing".</note> on
            the great mountain!</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
